Navigating with VoiceOver in Safari on Mac

02
On this page
  1. VoiceOver Navigation in Safari on Mac
  2. Navigating with the Tab key
  3. Navigating with the Arrow Keys
  4. Navigating with the VoiceOver Rotor
  5. Use Defaults Whenever Possible

VoiceOver Navigation in Safari on Mac

Open the Listings detail page in the Safari web browser to the CampSpots homepage, then launch VoiceOver by using Fn + CMD + F5. (On a Mac desktop keyboard, you can omit the Fn key.)

You can hit CTRL at any time to get VoiceOver to stop reading.

Navigating with the Tab key

As you might expect by now, you can navigate around the page using the Tab key. (You may need to adjust your Safari settings and OSX System Preferences to allow tabbing to all interactive controls: visit Safari > Preferences > Advanced and System Preferences > Keyboard > Shortcuts if you haven’t already.)

VoiceOver will find and read items that are either focusable by default or have a tabindex value of 0 applied to them.

If available, additional information may be read out and displayed on the screen.

For example, when VoiceOver reaches the location search box on the homepage it reads the label of the input, its placeholder, a role, and the landmark it’s in.

It will announce:

Where to? Try Oregon, Colorado..., edit text, main

Navigating with the Arrow Keys

Using the Arrow keys with VoiceOver running will cycle you through both static and interactive content on the page.

Sometimes Arrow key navigation will result in getting stuck in a focusable control like an input. When this happens, I either Tab to the next item, use another VoiceOver key shortcut, click elsewhere on the screen, or bail out of VoiceOver altogether.

These are my solutions as someone who is not a day-to-day screen reader user. This also highlights an important thing to remember: feedback from daily screen reader users is necessary when designing and developing accessible user interfaces.

However, there are also Arrow key navigation issues that are not the result of tester error!

I have encountered problems where interactive elements that are reachable by the Tab key can’t be reached with the Arrow keys.

If you run into this issue, it needs to be inspected. VoiceOver can definitely have some quirks that are worth debugging to ensure compatibility. But if you encounter similar issues in more popular Windows screen readers like NVDA or JAWS, by all means–prioritize those!

Navigating with the VoiceOver Rotor

Open the VoiceOver Rotor with CTRL + OPTION + U.

The VoiceOver Rotor allows us to navigate through collections of elements on the page. For example, you can cycle through all of the headings, landmarks, form controls, or links on a page.

Use right and left Arrow keys to cycle through the groups, then the up and down Arrow keys to highlight an item. Hit the Enter key to move to that item on the page.

Use Defaults Whenever Possible

VoiceOver has several methods of navigating a page so you don’t need to be overzealous with setting a tabindex in your components! For example, headings do not need to be keyboard-interactive to be readable with a screen reader.

Using proper elements and keeping a semantic structure will make the screen reader experience better.
